<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06200084 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06200084 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  HOMOSEXUAL; DISCRIMINATION; LAWSUIT; LOAN; SERVICE; COMPANY  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A gay consumer loan officer has sued his employer for denying him the chanceto take his male partner on a trip to London that he won for superiorperformance on the job.;    Lawrence James, the Pleasanton branch manager ofLos Angeles-based Transamerica Financial Services Corp., claims the companyhas allowed opposite sex, unmarried partners to go on such company-paid tripsin the past but balked when he said he was taking his male partner last summer.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Local  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  GAY BIAS CHARGED IN LOAN OFFICER SUIT  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Also ran p. 2B Alameda County Edition  </MEMO><TEXT>     James, in the suit filed last week in Alameda County Superior Court, saysthe company is violating California's fair employment laws and a San Franciscoordinance prohibiting discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation. Theconsumer loan company is a subsidiary of San Francisco-based TransamericaCorp.;    A spokesman for the company said James, who has worked forTransamerica since 1968, has &quot;totally mischaracterized&quot; the situation anddenied the company discriminates against anyone on the basis of sexualorientation.;    &quot;The rules that have long been in effect is if a winningmanager is married, then he or she may bring his or her spouse (on a trip),but if they are single, they are not allowed to bring a guest of anyrelationship,&quot; said Richard J. Olsen, Transamerica Corp.'s vice president forcorporate relations.;    Asked to respond to James' contention thatnon-married, opposite sex partners have gone on trips before, Olsen responded,&quot;Insofar as we're aware, that is not the case. . . . I cannot absolutely andcategorically say that someone hasn't put one over on us&quot; in the past.;   Both James and his Oakland attorney, Amy Oppenheimer, declined to comment onthe suit.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  BARRY WITT, Mercury News Oakland Bureau  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><CITY>  Oakland  </CITY><EDITION>  Santa Cruz/Monterey  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910718  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Thursday  </DAY><MONTH>  July  </MONTH><PG.COL>  1B  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  282  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Thursday July 18, 199100200084,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>